Some women tech experts have shared with entrepreneurs ways to use digital tools to promote their businesses online. The training was organised by Women’s Technology Empowerment Centre (W.TEC), to mark the 2022 International Women’s Day.   Stallion rolls out 100,000th locally-assembled Bajaj…     FAO moves to boost catfish production     ‘Ending tuberculosis requires greater funding’   Moderated by W.TEC Programme Manager, Folashade Braimoh, facilitators shared how participants could exploit virtual store fronts, set up payment instruments, advertise, and take advantage of merchandising platforms, such as Jumia and Konga, to enhance visibility, customer service delivery, among others, for their businesses. Programme Manager, Sub-Saharan Africa, Oracle Academy, Reporting and Business Intelligence Systemspecs Limited, Victoria Etim Bassey; Marketing Director Africa, Oracle Academy, Janet Kamau; and Continuous Improvement and Operational Excellence Lead at IBM, Kasia Garcia shared how important technology was to business success. Founder of W.TEC Oreoluwa Lesi said more still had to be done, besides inspiring girls but deliberately getting more women to contribute to the STEM field to balance the gender gap.